Heat a wide bottomed #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Pop the @lamb mince{250%g} into the pan and cook for ~{8-10%minutes} until browned. Use a #spoon{} to break it up, then get on with the rest of your prep.

Cut the @red onion{1}(in half through the root) in half through the root. Peel and then slice into thin half moon shapes. Remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1}(cored and thinly sliced) and thinly slice. Peel and grate the @ginger{1}(peeled and grated) and @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one).

Pop the @basmati rice{175%g} and @star anise{1} in a #pot{} with a good pinch of @salt{}. Pour in the @water for the rice{350%ml} and put the pot on high heat. When boiling, reduce the heat to medium, cover with a #lid{} and leave your rice to cook for ~{10%minutes}. After 10 mins, remove the pot from the heat and leave to one side for another ~{10%minutes} (with the lid still on). Your rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

When your mince has browned add the @mustard seeds{1%tsp}, onion and pepper. Cook for ~{5%minutes} and then add the @Sri Lankan curry powder{1.5%tbsp}, ginger and garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} more and then add the @tomato passata{1%small carton}. Bring to the boil, then add the @chicken stock pot{1/2%pot} and the @water{200%ml}. This is your curry!

Lower the heat until your curry is simmering gently and cook for ~{10-15%minutes} or until it has reduced by half.

As your curry cooks, finish off your last couple of jobs and then get any washing up done. Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(roughly chopped) and drain the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #colander{} and rinse under cold water.

When your curry has thickened, add your chickpeas and @baby spinach{1%bag}. Cook for ~{2%minutes} to ensure your chickpeas are piping hot and then remove from the heat. Taste your curry and add more @?salt{} and @?black pepper{} if necessary. Stir in your coriander.

Remove your star anise from your rice and fluff up your rice with a #fork{}. Check the seasoning and add more salt if necessary.

Spoon your rice onto your plates and serve your lamb and chickpea curry on top. Enjoy!

> This mouthwatering curry is really easy and quick to prepare! It is spiced with Sri Lankan curry powder and flavoured with ginger, garlic, coriander, mustard seeds and star anise - these herbs and spices are the stars of the dish and make, what is a really simple meal, fresh and delicious.